  "prompt": "How often do you buy new smart phones?",
  "response": "As an AI, I don't purchase or use smartphones, but I can provide some insights into how often people buy new smartphones based on general trends.\n\n1. **Average Consumer**: Many people typically upgrade their smartphones every 2-3 years. This is often tied to the end of their phone contract, the release of new models, or when their current device starts to slow down or have battery issues.\n\n2. **Tech Enthusiasts**: Some consumers, especially tech enthusiasts, may upgrade every year to get the latest features, improved performance, or new design elements.\n\n3. **Budget-Conscious Users**: Others might keep their phones for 4 years or more, especially if they are satisfied with their current device and want to save money. They may also opt for battery replacements or repairs to extend their phone's lifespan.\n\n4. **Market Trends**: The introduction of new features (e.g., 5G, foldable screens, AI advancements) can also influence the frequency of upgrades.\n\nUltimately, how often someone buys a new smartphone depends on their needs, budget, and interest in new technology.",
